e. Official satire and humor in Soviet Lithuania increasingly created dystopian visions of Soviet modernity and were a forum for critical ideas and nationalist sentiments that were mobilized in anti-Soviet revolutionary laughter in the late 1980s and early 1990s. Authoritarian Laughter illustrates that Soviet Western peripheries were unstable and their governance was limited. While authoritarian states engage in a statecraft of the everyday and seek to engineer intimate lives, authoritarianism is defied not only in revolutions, but in the many stories people tell each other about themselves in jokes, cartoons, and satires.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aPolitical satire, Lithuanian. 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Baltic States.2bisacsh  abroom satire and humor magazine, soviet humor propaganda in lithuania, soviet political humor in lithuania, soviet satirical magazine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176670140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501766701423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501766701/original  a978-3-11-075182-6  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK